Californians voted to fund embryonic stem cell research, previously banned by President Bush.
The measure aims to position California as a global hub for stem cell research, potentially leading to cures for diseases like cancer and Alzheimer's.
The emotionally charged Proposition 71 passed with 64% support, allocating nearly $3 billion over 10 years.
Stem cell research has shown promise in treating Parkinson's disease, with dopamine playing a crucial role.
Additionally, a gene mutation linked to Parkinson's was discovered, offering new avenues for research.
The potential of embryonic stem cells in finding cures for various diseases is a focal point of ongoing scientific exploration.
